occurrences.line_text: And kissing oft his visage pale and wan.
In her faire visage voide of ornament,
Cursing his hand that had that visage mard:
To hide the blush which in her visage rose,
Their visages imprest, when they approched neare.
And greedy Rosmarines with visages deforme.
Through that late vision, which th'Enchaunter wrought,
Were vnto him reueald in vision,
Shalbe by vision staid from his intent:
To be no vision, nor fantasticke sight,
Did worship her as some celestiall vision.
A wondrous vision, which did close implie
Of all that vision, which to her appeard,
Shewes, visions, sooth-sayes, and prophesies;
And dreadfull visions, in the which aliue
Where shee strange visions sees:
As was his vse, ofttimes to visit me:
To visite her beloued Paramoure,
To visite, after this nights perillous passe,
And but halfe seene his vgly visnomie,
By which deceipt doth maske in visour faire,
And bowd his battred visour to his brest:
Dead is Sans-foy, his vitall paines are past,
In slombring swownd nigh voyd of vitall spright,
Were cleane consum'd, and all his vitall powres
And doen the heauens afford him vitall food?
That vitall powres gan wexe both weake and wan,
Gan sucke this vitall aire into his brest,
As other wemens babes, they sucked vitall blood.
That fed on liuing flesh, & druncke mens vitall blood.
And fading vitall powers gan to fade,
That from one roote deriu'd their vitall sap:
That with the wasting of his vitall flood,
And all her vitall powres with motion nimble,
That all his vitall spirites thereby spild,
So all things else, that nourish vitall blood,
And of their vitall bloud, the which was shed
And euen to the vitall parts they past,
As if her vitall powers were at strife
His vitall breath, and to the ground him bore,
Corrupts the stomacke with gall vitious,
Of that Argante vile and vitious,
And th'vlcer groweth daily more and more;
Great Vlfin thrise vpon the bloudy plaine,
But onely vented vp her vmbriere,
And therewith smote him on his Vmbriere
The fairest Vn' his onely daughter deare,
Cast a blacke stole, most like to seeme for Vna fit.
And Vna wandring in woods and forrests,
Dame Vna, wearie Dame, and entrance did requere.
Faire Vna framed words and count'nance fit:
Sad Vna downe her laies in wearie plight,
Vp Vna rose, vp rose the Lyon eke,
But subtill Archimag, that Vna sought
Ere long he came, where Vna traueild slow,
Such ioy made Vna, when her knight she found;
Till Vna cride, O hold that heauie hand,
Who after that he had faire Vna lorne,
fayre Vna is releast:
And yet more sad, that Vna his deare dreed
Where he vnwares the fairest Vna found,
Then Vna gan to aske, if ought he knew,
Whiles Vna with huge heauinesse opprest,
Faire Vna: whom when Satyrane espide,
By this sad Vna fraught with anguish sore,
Prince Arthur meets with Vna great-
He wofull Ladie, wofull Vna met,
To do her dye (quoth Vna) were despight,
Such then (said Vna) as she seemeth here,
But that faire crew of knights, and Vna faire
But ere they parted, Vna faire besought
Till gentle Vna thus to him gan say;
Als Vna earnd her traueill to renew.
Which when as Vna saw, through euery vaine
Her faithfull knight faire Vna brings
By that, which lately hapned, Vna saw,
Where when that fairest Vna she beheld,
They seeing Vna, towards her gan wend,
Then Vna thus; But she your sister deare;
Faire Vna gan Fidelia faire request,
When him his dearest Vna did behold,
His owne deare Vna hearing euermore
And trew Repentance they to Vna brought:
To her faire Vna brought this vnacquainted guest.
The knight and Vna entring, faire her greet,
Then Vna her besought, to be so good,
To Vna back he cast him to retire;
So came to Vna, who him ioyd to see,
High time now gan it wex for Vna faire,
When gentle Vna saw the second fall
About her eares, when Vna her did marke
Faire Vna to the Redcrosse knight
The which he shortly did, and Vna left to mourne.
Sith Vna now he algates must forgoe,
He that faire Vna late fowle outraged,
And vanquisht them, vnable to withstand:
Perforse him pluckt, vnable to withstand,
Vnable to arise, or foot or hand to styre.
And finding him vnable once to weld,
He now vnable was to wreake his old despight.
Vnable he new battell to darraine,
He may them catch, vnable to gainestriue,
Like ruefull ghost, vnable once to stirre or moue.
Being vnable to digest that bone;
That his great force vnable to endure,
As he vnable were for very neede
So as it was vnable to support
To Fortunes spoile, vnable it to ayd.
And th'vnacquainted light began to feare:
To her faire Vna brought this vnacquainted guest.
Thether he brought these vnacquainted guests;
Through vnaduized rashnesse woxen wood;
For fairest Vnaes sake, of whom I sing,
With Vnaes foe, that all her realme did pray.
They turne themselues, at Vnaes meeke request,
That to all vertue it may seeme vnapt,
To be vnarmd, and curld vncombed heares
Halfe armd and halfe vnarmd, with them attons:
Ne surely thus vnarm'd I likely were;
For armed knight a wight vnarm'd to wrong.
Vnarm'd all was the knight, as then more meete
This knight vnarm'd, with so vnknightly breach
And him vnarm'd, as now he lay on ground,
Being vnarm'd, and set in secret shade.
Vnarm'd, as fearing neither foe nor frend,
Which his right hand vnarmed fearefully did wield.
Both armed Knights, and eke vnarmed rout:
By Arthure, when as Vnas Knight he did maintaine.
Both vnassaylable, gaue him great ayde:
For feare least Force or Fraud should vnaware
The Blatant Beast forth rushing vnaware,
Or vnawares at disauantage found;
And vnawares vpon her laying hold,
All vnawares he started vp anon,
Through misconceipt; all vnawares espide
Whiles vnawares his saddle he forwent,
Had vnawares her snatched vp from ground.
All vnawares the bird, when she did find
An headlesse heape, him vnawares there caught,
Those gates to be vnbar'd, and forth he went.
He running downe, the gate to him vnbard;
She bad that streight the gates should be vnbard,
And with it hung himselfe, vnbid vnblest.
The loyall links of wedlocke did vnbind,
Nine monethes I seeke in vaine yet ni'll that vow vnbind.
His blindfold eyes he bad a while vnbind,
To know, what Virgin did them thence vnbind;
Therefore I cast, how I may him vnbind,
In her false hart, his bondage to vnbind;
He first her hands beginneth to vnbind,
As did Pyrrochles, and it wilfully vnbindes.
And Furors chayne vnbinds
Ioying together in vnblam'd delight,
To blot your beautie, that vnblemisht is,
And with it hung himselfe, vnbid vnblest.
To shame vs all with this, Vngirt vnblest.
Into the floud: streight leapt the Carle vnblest,
They saw that Carle from farre, with hand vnblest
He bad his eyes to be vnblindfold both,
Th'immortall name, with which thee yet vnborne
And all the sleights vnbosomd in his hart;
His griesie lockes, long growen, and vnbound,
That like a ghost he seem'd, whose graue-clothes were vnbound.
What bootes it him from death to be vnbound,
Tho when she felt her selfe to be vnbound,
Th'abandond spoyle, he softly it vnbound;
All in her snow-white smocke, with locks vnbownd,
Eftsoones him selfe he from his hold vnbownd,
Knit all his forces, and gan soone vnbrace
And her lancke loynes vngirt, and brests vnbraste,
To perils great; which he vnbuckling eft,
As selfe to dyen bad, vnburied bad to beene.
And their vile carcases now left vnburied.
Shall vs restore, none else from hence may vs vnbynd.
Till Fortune would her captiue bonds vnbynde:
There Braggadochio is vncas'd
Now when these counterfeits were thus vncased
But a faint shadow of vncertain light;
And yet vncertaine by such outward sight,
Vncertaine whether had the better side:
But stood long staring on him, mongst vncertaine feares.
That made him stagger with vncertaine sway,
With wearie trauell and vncertaine toile,
There by th'vncertaine glimse of starry night,
That ye doe tell in such vncertaintee?
But wandreth euer more vncertein and vnsure.
Seeking to match the chaste with th'vnchaste Ladies traine.
But by the change of her vnchearefull looke,
An vncouth, saluage, and vnciuile wight,
Of that vile hag, or her vnciuile sonne:
Whilest he reformed that vnciuill fo:
By meanes whereof, their vncle Vortigere
Which follow'd her, with cursed hands vncleane
Through vaine illusion of their lust vnclene,
And enuious of Vncles soueraintie,
Vncomb'd, vncurl'd, and carelesly vnshed;
To be vnarmd, and curld vncombed heares
And with vncomely weedes the gentle waue accloyes.
Headed like Owles, with beckes vncomely bent,
Ne suffereth it vncomely idlenesse,
And further did vncomely speaches crake.
That his bigge hart loth'd so vncomely vew.
And causd him those vncomely weedes vndight;
He was ymett, who with vncomely shame
To weet the cause of so vncomely fray,
And shrieked out, a thing vncomely for a knight.
How fortuneth this foule vncomely plight,
Throughout the world, in this vncomely case,
So inward shame of her vncomely case
And to the last vnconquer'd did appeare;
And vncontrolled freedome to obtaine.
And eke thy words vncourteous and vnkempt;
Soone as that vncouth light vpon them shone,
All cleane dismayd to see so vncouth sight,
All stand amazed at so vncouth sight,
The greatest Earth his vncouth mother was,
But very vncouth sight was to behold,
Vpstaring stiffe, dismayd with vncouth dread;
That with the vncouth smart the Monster lowdly cryde.
He weened well to worke some vncouth wile,
So now he Guyon guides an vncouth way
Great cause, I weene, you guided, or some vncouth chaunce.
Whiles Guyon standing by, their vncouth strife does see.
For much he wondred at that vncouth sight;
An vncouth, saluage, and vnciuile wight,
That Guyon meruayld at her vncouth cace:
Who when his vncouth manner he did vew,
To aske this Briton Mayd, what vncouth wind,
What vncouth fit (said she) what euill plight
Of much more vncouth thing I was affrayd;
His vncouth shield and straunge armes her dismayd,
And vncouth formes, which none yet euer knew,
Through many a wood, and many an vncouth way,
And with such vncouth welcome did receaue
Of th'vncouth sight, as he some ghost had seene,
That all men wondred at the vncouth sight,
To be spectators of this vncouth fit,
At which his vncouth guise and vsage quaint
That them to view had bene an vncouth sight;
And vncouth fashion, yet her well became;
To view the building of that vncouth place,
(An vncouth sight) he plainely then descride
Much did he maruell at her vncouth speach,
And doubtfully dismayd through that so vncouth sight.
Where when she saw that lothly vncouth sight,
And on his backe an vncouth vestiment
Which vncouth vse when as the Prince perceiued,
That mote to all men seeme an vncouth sight;
Ne skilfull of the vncouth ieopardy;
What meaning mote those vncouth words comprize,
Vncomb'd, vncurl'd, and carelesly vnshed;
And that vncurteous Carle their commune foe
The law of armes, to strike foe vndefide.
Dan Chaucer, well of English vndefyled,
Vnder a vele, that wimpled was full low,
And said, Faire knight, borne vnder happy starre,
Whose semblance she did carrie vnder feigned hew.
Vnder blake stole hyding her bayted hooke,
He that the wide West vnder his rule has,
Vnder them neuer sat, ne wont there sound
Vnder my speare: such is the dye of warre:
Nought there vnder heau'ns wilde hollownesse,
Vnder the steepe foot of a mountaine hore;
Vnder his Lordly foot him proudly hath supprest.
From vnder which fast trickled downe the sweat:
Vnder your beames I will me safely shrowd,
And placed vnder stately canapee,
Low vnder all, yet aboue all in pride,
As when a ship, that flyes faire vnder saile,
The ground eke groned vnder him for dreed;
O great Orgoglio, greatest vnder skye,
At euery little breath, that vnder heauen is blowne.
Who vnder him did trample as the aire,
Vnder the foot of Rauran mossy hore,
And made wide shadow vnder his huge wast;
Close vnder his left wing, then broad displayd.
And thou, O fairest Princesse vnder sky,
But vnder him a gray steede did he wield,
But vnder simple shew and semblant plaine
Lurking in rockes and caues farre vnder ground,
Ah lucklesse babe, borne vnder cruell starre,
So fortune wrought, as vnder greene woods syde
Vnder the shadow of her euen browes,
Before they fastned were vnder her knee
To whom he thus: ï¿½ fairest vnder skie,
Vnder Sir Guyons puissaunt stroke to fall,
Death is for wretches borne vnder vnhappie starre.
And that aboue were added to that vnder ground.
Of euery sort and nation vnder skye,
The fairest wight that wonneth vnder skye,
That drenched lay full deepe, vnder the Garden side.
Most cursed of all creatures vnder skye,
When vnder him he saw his Lybian steed to praunce.
And through his nimble sleight did vnder him down cast.
And wind his horne vnder the castle wall,
Ne vnder Sunne, that shines so wide and faire,
Three sonnes he dying left, all vnder age;
That all the land they vnder them did hide;
And vnder neath him his courageous steed,
And many arrowes vnder his right side,
Or aerie spirit vnder false pretence,
Vnder the ship, as thorough them she went,
Vnder that Porch a comely dame did rest,
So held them vnder fast, the whiles the rest
That seem'd to couch vnder his shield three-square,
And treading vnder foote her honest name:
(For she her sexe vnder that straunge purport
And vnder the blacke vele of guilty Night,
Vnder what coast of heauen the man did dwell,
Vnder a rocke that lyes a little space
From vnder that deepe Rocke most horribly rebounds.
He was surprisd, and buried vnder beare,
Vnder thy mantle blacke there hidden lye,
Which seeme to labour vnder their fruits lode:
Vnder a mightie rocke, gainst which do raue
Whose fruitlesse liues were vnder furrow sowne,
Of all the world vnder her gouerning.
Which quaked vnder their so hideous masse,
Which houed close vnder a forrest side,
The huge seas vnder her t'obay her seruaunts law.
A wounded Dragon vnder him did ly,
Vnder his eyebrowes looking still askaunce;
For vnder maske of beautie and good grace,
It is a darksome delue farre vnder ground,
That vnder great Alcides furie fell:
The other downe vnder their horses feete,
That vnder it hidde hate and hollow guyle.
Farre vnder ground from tract of liuing went,
And rudely tumbling downe vnder his horse feete fell.
By shiuered speares, and swords all vnder strowen,
Vnder a steepe hilles side it placed was,
Vnder his side him nipt, that forst to wake,
An armed Knight vnder a forrest side,
Ne wist whether aboue she were, or vnder ground.
Vnder his arme, as seeming wondrous glad,
With that she askt, what ghosts there vnder ground
She were as faire as any vnder skie.
Like to a storme, which houers vnder skie
I count as naught, and tread downe vnder feet,
Both male and female, both vnder one name:
The ioy of Gods and men, that vnder skie
Vnder his Diademe imperiall:
His way still vnder ground, till Thamis he ouertake.
And many riuers taking vnder hand
Vnder Slewbloome in shady groue was got,
From vnder which the deawy humour shed,
Vnder the which, her feet appeared plaine,
Vnder the hanging of an hideous clieffe,
But closely rankled vnder th'orifis:
Vnder the Sea-gods seale autenticall,
Vnder an heape of gold. Thence he her drew
Encroch vppon the land there vnder thee;
And weigh the winde, that vnder heauen doth blow;
From euery coast and countrie vnder sunne:
Vnder my foote let each lay downe his sword,
Vnder the wings of Isis all that night,
Vnder the Idols feete in fearelesse bowre,
That vnder Isis feete doth sleepe for euer:
Nought vnder heauen so strongly doth allure
Serues her, as any Princesse vnder sky,
Or to his part allures, and bribeth vnder hand.
Or vnder his fierce horses feet haue borne
Is wondrous strong, and hewen farre vnder ground
That vnder shew oftimes of fayned semblance,
Vnder Alcides club, streight tooke his flight
Vnder that cursed Idols altar stone;
But ryding streight vnder the Castle wall,
There forth issewd, from vnder th'Altars smooke,
Vnder her wombe his fatall sword he thrust,
Vnder one hood to shadow faces twaine.
Vnder his stroke he to him stepping neare,
And euery part, that vnder sweathbands lay,
At length he heard vnder the forrests syde
And with her husband vnder hand so wrought,
Vnder the greenewoods side in sorie plight,
Seem'd vnder her protection him to shroud;
Vnder that villaines club, then surely thought
Vnder his club with wary boldnesse went,
Which tosseth states, and vnder foot doth tread
But being bred vnder base shepheards wings,
She should it cause be fostred vnder straunge attyre.
Whilest Calidore him vnder him downe threw;
And some by sleight he eke doth vnderfong.
Hath long bene vnderkept, and downe supprest,
Rored, and raged to be vnder-kept:
But with slie shiftes and wiles did vnderminde
So striuing each th'other to vndermine,
Is vndermined from the lowest ground
Lo vnderneath her scornefull feete, was layne
Which vnderneath did hide his filthinesse,
And vnderneath their feet, all scattered lay
The bold Sansfoy shrinke vnderneath his speare;
Forth ryding vnderneath the castell wall,
And lightly lept from vnderneath the blow:
And vnderneath his filthy feet did tread
Did grone full grieuous vnderneath the blow,
Whose blessed sprites from vnderneath the stone
And haue beene thrice hid vnderneath the ground,
Farre vnderneath a craggie clift ypight,
So downe he fell, that th'earth him vnderneath
And all the floore was vnderneath their feet
Faire marching vnderneath a shady hill,
Loe this dead corpse, that lies here vnderneath,
But prickt so fiers, that vnderneath his feete
Was vnderneath enueloped with gold,
That vnderneath his feet soone made a purple plesh.
That as the winde ran vnderneath his lode,
The rest hid vnderneath, him more desirous made.
So vnderneath her feet their swords they mard,
And her soft arme lay vnderneath his hed,
To make his wonne, low vnderneath the ground,
Hewen vnderneath that Mount, that none him losen may.
And vnderneath his feet was written thus,
With doubled force close vnderneath his shield,
Close vnderneath his shield, that scarce did show,
And vnderneath, the riuer rolling still
And vnderneath the same a riuer flowes,
And vnderneath his breech was all to torne and iagged.
Whylest vnderneath her feete, there as she sate,
And vnderneath this Idoll there doth lie
The Monster vnderneath the Altar lay;
Did vnderneath him like a pond appeare,
Strooke him, as seemeth, vnderneath the hart,
And layd her vnderneath a bush to sleepe,
Did vnderneath them make a gloomy shade;
And beat them back, whilest many vnderneath him fell.
And vnderneath thy feete to place her prayse;
For vnderneath the ground their way was made,
Had vnderneath, him armed priuily.
But trembled vnderneath his mighty hand,
She could not heare, nor speake, nor vnderstand;
Ne dare to weepe, nor seeme to vnderstand
And feates of armes did wisely vnderstand.
The course of heauenly cause, or vnderstand
Those tydings were, as he did vnderstand,
Suffice it heare by signes to vnderstand
Assur'd, ere long the truth to let me vnderstand.
How brutish is it not to vnderstand,
And lent her wary eare to vnderstand,
Her now I seeke, and if ye vnderstand
They sent that Squire afore, to vnderstand,
The day was set, that all might vnderstand,
Yet goldsmithes cunning could not vnderstand
As if she would haue made him vnderstand,
Whose substance was vneath to vnderstand:
Whose counsels depth thou canst not vnderstand,
And then you shall my sentence vnderstand.
But vertuous women wisely vnderstand,
To vnderstand that villeins dwelling place,
Which that those knights likewise mote vnderstand,
Then thou, that shall thy treason vnderstand,
She then, like as she best could vnderstand,
To vnderstand what there was to be donne.
Or vnderstand, that she in safetie did remaine.
Now mote ye vnderstand that to this groue
Through secret vnderstanding of their feature.
Who vnderstanding by her mightie art,
Soone as the Redcrosse knight he vnderstands,
her parents vnderstands:
Vnto that stead, their strife to vnderstond;
Their countries auncestry to vnderstond,
Which when his mother deare did vnderstond,
And euery where that he mote vnderstond,
Wherein darke things were writ, hard to be vnderstood.
And told for secret how he vnderstood
They wondred much, and shortly vnderstood,
And Glaucus, that wise southsayes vnderstood;
And vnderstood the cause of all her care
Where when he vnderstood by common fame,
That what of it became, none vnderstood.
To hide thy state from being vnderstood?
Well vnderstood, he gan of her demand,
Whose vertue he by vse well vnderstood:
Which when her father vnderstood, he grew
Askt her, how mote her words be vnderstood,
Aboue all knights on earth, that batteill vndertake.
The same by my deuice I vndertake
That none of them durst vndertake the fight;
Whom on his perill he did vndertake,
Whose voice so soone as he did vndertake,
Nor vndertake the same, for cowheard feare,
That euer I for meed did vndertake
Had vndertaken after her, arriu'd,
Which he had vndertane to Gloriane;
He comming home at vndertime, there found
All which he vndertooke for to repaire,
That I must rue his vndeserued wrong:
The vndeserued woes and sorrowes, which ye shew.
That she gan mone his vndeserued smart,
And doft his helmet, and vndid his mayle:
That cruell Atropos eftsoones vndid,
Sir Artegall vndid the euill fashion,
From her faire head her fillet she vndight,
Which when she saw, she left her lockes vndight,
His mayled haberieon she did vndight,
Now loose about her shoulders hong vndight,
And welcomed themselues. Each gan vndight
And causd him those vncomely weedes vndight;
For his loues sake his Lions skin vndight:
His warlike armes he had from him vndight:
